{"cursor":"2453","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nA 'rotary [[switch]]' is a switch operated by rotation. These are often chosen\nwhen more than 2 positions are needed, such as a three-speed fan or a CB radio\nwith multiple frequencies of reception or \"channels\".\n\n\n\n\n\nA rotary switch consists of a spindle or \"\" that has a contact arm or \"spoke\"\nwhich projects from its surface like a cam. It has an array of terminals,\narranged in a circle around the rotor, each of which serves as a contact for the\n\"spoke\" through which any one of a number of different electrical circuits can\nbe connected to the rotor. The switch is layered to allow the use of multiple\npoles, each layer is equivalent to one pole. Usually such a switch has a detent\nmechanism so it \"clicks\" from one active position to another rather than stalls\nin an intermediate position. Thus a rotary switch provides greater pole and\nthrow capabilities than simpler switches do.\n\nRotary switches were used as channel selectors on television receivers until the\nearly 1970s, as range selectors on electrical metering equipment, as band\nselectors on multi-band radios, etc.\n\nModern rotary switches utilise a \"star wheel\" mechanism to provide the\nswitching positions. 30,45,60 or 90 degrees. Nylon cams are then mounted behind\nthis mechanism and spring-loaded electrical contacts slide around these cams.\nThe cams are notched or cut where the contact should close to complete an\nelectrical circuit.\n\nSome rotary switches are user configurable in relation to the number of\npositions. A special toothed washer that sits below the holding nut can be\npositioned so that the tooth is inserted into one of a number of slots in a way\nthat limits the number of positions available for selection. For example, if\nonly four positions are required on a twelve position switch, the washer can be\npositioned so that only four switching positions can be selected when in use.\n","linknr":109,"url":"Rotary_switch","recorded":1374761188,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Rotary_switch&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Rotary_switch&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Rotary_system","/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources","/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Rotary_switch&action=edit","/wiki/Help:Introduction_to_referencing/1","/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability#Burden_of_evidence","/wiki/Switch","/wiki/Fan_(implement)","/wiki/CB_radio","/wiki/Frequency","/wiki/File:Rotaryswitch.gif","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Rotaryswitch.gif/360px-Rotaryswitch.gif","/wiki/File:Rotaryswitch.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/File:Twelve_position_rotary_switch_contacts_view.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7f/Twelve_position_rotary_switch_contacts_view.jpg/220px-Twelve_position_rotary_switch_contacts_view.jpg","/wiki/File:Twelve_position_rotary_switch_contacts_view.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wik